The first step before doing any dimensionality reduce method is to have an idea about the relation of features. Some columns may be strongly related and others can be independant. Using our dataset, we can compute a correlation matrix to observe our 12 features and have a first idea.

As we saw with the describe() method, some features have some disparities. For example the minimum and maximum value for the "fixed acidity" feature are respectively 3.80 and 14.20, while the miminimum and maximum value for the "volatile acidity" feature are respectively 0.08 and 1.10. To address this we need to standardize the dataset.

In [5]:
data["quality label"] = ""
for i in range(len(data)):
    if 0 <= data.iloc[i]["quality"] <= 4:
        data.at[i,"quality label"] = "Bad"
    elif 5 <= data.iloc[i]["quality"] <= 6:
        data.at[i,"quality label"] = "Medium"
    elif data.iloc[i]["quality"] >= 7:
        data.at[i,"quality label"] = "Excellent"

II - Dimension reduction¶

II.1 - PCA¶

In [11]:

nb_components = 11

pca.fit(data_scaled)

In [12]:
def display_scree_plot(pca):
    scree = pca.explained_variance_ratio_*100
    plt.bar(np.arange(len(scree))+1, scree)
    plt.plot(np.arange(len(scree))+1, scree.cumsum(),c="red",marker='o')
    plt.xlabel("PCA components",fontsize=10)
    plt.ylabel("percentage of information",fontsize=10)
    plt.title("Scree plot",fontsize=20)
    plt.show(block=False)

display_scree_plot(pca)

According to the plot above, we need minimum 7 components to get 87% of information. We can have more precision about those value with the explained variance cumulative sum method.

We can see from both dimension reduction methods that the number of components needed is different. For the PCA method, we have seen that we need minimum 7 components to keep 87% of information. But for the LDA method, according to the scree plot we only need the first two components to keep 94% of information. Furthermore, we have to remind that PCA retains the most valuable information from all the variables but then we can no longer interpret the features where as with the LDA, as it is a supervised dimension reduction method, we can still interpret the features. Unfortunately, LDA visualization seems to be like PCA's one, we can't see clearly the repartition.
Let's see a vizualisation with each component of the PCA to check if there are any repartitions:

In [33]:

In [34]:
sns.pairplot(df, height=2.5, diag_kind=None, hue="target");

Here we can clearly see that whatever the components, there is not a good repartition.

If PCA and LDA don't work, it means that our features either have non-linear relationships or no relationship at all. That could possibily mean that Wine Quality column is not correlated to Wine attributes in linear manner.

LDA and PCA are components/Factors based dimensionality reduction method. Let's try Projection based methods such as t-SNE or Isomap to check if we can have a good visualition with those methods.

During this project we tried to reduce the dimensionality of the wine quality dataset to be able to focus on the most important features. So we first tried component/factor based dimensionality reduction method such as PCA and LDA. As expected those methods reduced the dimension of our dataset while keeping most of the information from the original dataset, however they were not able to propose a clear repartition of the data. That could possibly mean that our features either have non-linear relationships or no relationship at all. So we decided to use projection based method such as t-sne and isomap. Unfortunately, the results were not clear either. The reason is that the feature "quality" is given by an oenologist, it means that the relation between the feature "quality" and the components of the wine is not that strong. The quality of a wine is a feature that is a little bit biased, indeed an excellent wine can have a totally different composition than another excellent wine. One solution could be to use clustering to improve the repartition of the data in order to facilitate the prediction step.
